            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this long-term care cost calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Long-term care (LTC) can be one of the largest expenses in
                retirement. This calculator helps you estimate how much care
                might cost in the future and how much you may need to pay out of
                pocket.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Baseline monthly cost today</h3>
              <p>
                You can either start from typical national median costs by care
                type or enter a custom monthly quote. For presets, we use
                approximate national medians (rounded) in today’s dollars:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>In-home care (aide 44 hrs/week):</strong> about
                  <code>$5,500/month</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Assisted living facility:</strong> about
                  <code>$5,000/month</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Nursing home (private room):</strong> about
                  <code>$9,500/month</code>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Memory care:</strong> about
                  <code>$7,000/month</code> (often 20–40% above assisted living)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The “Adjust for your area” slider scales these medians up or
                down (for example, 120% for a high-cost city, 80% for a
                lower-cost region).
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Adjusted current monthly cost</strong><br />
                \( \text{CurrentMonthly} = \text{BaselineMonthly} \times
                \dfrac{\text{Area%}}{100} \)
              </div>

              <h3>2. Projecting costs with inflation</h3>
              <p>
                Long-term care costs rarely stay flat. We project the cost
                forward from today until the year you expect care to begin using
                a compound inflation rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Future monthly cost at start of care</strong><br />
                \( \text{FutureMonthly} = \text{CurrentMonthly} \times (1 +
                i)^{n} \)<br />
                where:
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \( i \) = annual LTC inflation rate (e.g., 0.035 for 3.5%)
                  </li>
                  <li>\( n \) = years until care may start</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you set “Years until care may start” to 0, the calculator
                assumes care begins now and skips the inflation step.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Total cost of care and your share</h3>
              <p>
                Once we know the projected monthly cost at the start of care, we
                estimate the total cost over the number of years you selected:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Total cost of care (all sources)</strong><br />
                \( \text{TotalCost} = \text{FutureMonthly} \times 12 \times
                \text{YearsOfCare} \)
              </div>
              <p>
                You can then specify what percentage you expect to be covered by
                long-term care insurance, Medicaid, or other sources. The
                remainder is your out-of-pocket share:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Your out-of-pocket cost</strong><br />
                \( \text{OOP} = \text{TotalCost} \times \left(1 -
                \dfrac{\text{Coverage%}}{100}\right) \)
              </div>

              <h3>4. Simple savings target</h3>
              <p>
                To give you a rough savings goal, the calculator assumes you
                want to have the full out-of-pocket amount available at the
                start of care and that you earn no investment return (a
                conservative assumption):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Lump sum needed at start of care</strong><br />
                \( \text{LumpSum} = \text{OOP} \)
                <br /><br />
                <strong>Approximate monthly saving needed</strong><br />
                \( \text{MonthlySaving} = \dfrac{\text{LumpSum}}{n \times 12} \)
                <br />
                where \( n \) is the years until care may start.
              </div>
              <p>
                In reality, your investments may grow over time, which could
                reduce the monthly amount you need to save. A financial planner
                or advisor can refine this using your specific return and tax
                assumptions.
              </p>

              <h2>Choosing realistic assumptions</h2>

              <h3>Inflation rate for long-term care</h3>
              <p>Consider the following when choosing an inflation rate:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>2–3%:</strong> closer to general inflation; may be
                  optimistic for LTC.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>3–4%:</strong> common planning range for long-term
                  care costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>5%+:</strong> conservative, often used for younger
                  clients or high-cost markets.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How many years of care to plan for?</h3>
              <p>
                Average long-term care use is often cited as around 2–3 years,
                but there is wide variation. Some people never need care; others
                may need 5–10 years, especially with dementia or other chronic
                conditions.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>3–5 years:</strong> moderate planning horizon for many
                  households.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>5–8+ years:</strong> more conservative, often used
                  when there is a family history of cognitive decline.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Ways to pay for long-term care</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator only estimates costs; it does not recommend how
                to pay for them. Common funding sources include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Personal savings and investments</strong> (taxable
                  accounts, IRAs, 401(k)s, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Long-term care insurance</strong> or
                  <strong>hybrid life/LTC policies</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Home equity</strong> (downsizing, reverse mortgage, or
                  sale).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Family support</strong> (informal caregiving or
                  financial help).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Medicaid</strong> for those who meet strict income and
                  asset limits.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Medicare generally covers only short-term skilled nursing or
                rehabilitation—not ongoing custodial long-term care. That’s why
                advance planning is so important.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and next steps</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is for education and planning only. Actual long-term
                care costs will depend on your health, location, facility
                choice, and policy details if you have insurance. It does not
                replace personalized advice from a licensed financial planner,
                insurance professional, or elder law attorney.
              </p>
              <p>
                Use the results as a starting point for conversations with your
                family and advisors about how you would prefer to receive care
                and how you might fund it.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is long-term care insurance worth the cost?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on your age, health, assets, and risk tolerance.
                Insurance can protect savings from very high care costs, but
                premiums can be significant and may increase over time. Many
                people use a mix of insurance and self-funding. Comparing the
                projected cost of care from this calculator with potential
                policy benefits can help you decide.
              </p>

              <h3>What if I never need long-term care?</h3>
              <p>
                That is possible. Planning for LTC is about managing a risk that
                may or may not occur. Some people prefer to self-insure and
                accept the risk; others prefer to transfer some of the risk to
                an insurer. Even if you never need formal care, having extra
                savings can still support other retirement goals.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I update my long-term care plan?</h3>
              <p>
                Consider revisiting your assumptions every few years, or after
                major life events (retirement, diagnosis of a chronic condition,
                death of a spouse, large move). Costs, inflation, and your
                health status can all change over time.
              </p>
